				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">KennyB wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">PS/ Why does ASM 6502 have no LSL and/or ASR opcode ? I assume there is no difference between a Logical Shift and an Arithmetic Shift ?<br />Why then, haven't they used either LSR+LSL or ASR+ASL ? Instead of a combo of the two ?</div><br />The &quot;logical&quot; in the shift instructions mostly means &quot;always shifts in a 0&quot;. &quot;arithmetic&quot; mostly means &quot;does something appropriate rather than just always shift in 0&quot;. If they actually provided an ASR instruction, it would shift bits 7-1 down to 6-0 and then copy bit 6 back to bit 7. But on an 8 bit micro, it's not clear that's useful; any time you're doing other than 8-bit binary math you'll only use that once, and you may as well force them to write it out longhand (<tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">CMP #$80</tt>, <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">ROR</tt>)<br /><br />I'm going to arbitrarily guess they chose the pair of ASL+LSR to make the two instructions more visually distinct (and make it easier to catch bugs?).</div>

